## 1. Task Intent Interpretation
### 1.1 Problem Summary
This task bundles the first-generation user-facing account surfaces: profile pages, profile editing, settings, avatar upload, and core layout/navigation. Today, NuttyFans lacks a coherent “account and identity” area and a reusable layout/navigation skeleton, which blocks many PRD stories around users managing their presence and moving through the app.

### 1.2 Goals
- Let users see and manage their public-facing profile.
- Provide a basic settings surface for account and preference controls (non-payment, non-creator).
- Enable avatar upload so profiles feel personal and recognizable.
- Establish baseline layout and navigation that other features can plug into.

### 1.3 Related PRD/BRD References
- PRD §2.1.1 Account Management: U-001, U-004, U-006.
- BRD goals around **premium experience** and **creator-first** presentation (profiles are a core expression of this).

---

## 2. Scope Clarification
### 2.1 In Scope (Refined)
- **User profile pages**
  - Basic “My profile” view.
  - Basic “Other user” profile view (at least username/avatar/bio).
- **Profile editing**
  - Core profile fields (see Section 3).
  - Simple success/error feedback.
- **Settings page**
  - Account and basic preference settings (no payments, no creator monetization settings).
- **Avatar upload**
  - Upload/replace/remove avatar image using existing storage approach.
- **Basic layout components**
  - App shell (header/nav + content area).
  - Reusable containers/sections for pages.
- **Navigation implementation**
  - At minimum: entry points to Home/Feed, Profile, Settings.

### 2.2 Explicitly Out of Scope
- Creator page design, creator monetization settings, and analytics dashboards.
- Admin views of users and profiles.
- Detailed notification preference matrix.
- Payment, subscription, and payout-related settings.
- Complex information architecture beyond immediate primary nav needs.

---

## 3. Functional Requirements (Draft)
### 3.1 User Profile Data (Conceptual)
High-level fields for user-facing profile (exact schema is an architecture decision, not defined here):
- Display name.
- Username/handle.
- Avatar.
- Short bio/about.
- Location (optional, if allowed by legal/privacy).
- Join date (read-only display).
- Basic follower/following counts (display-only, if available).

### 3.2 Profile Pages
- FR-PROFILE-001: Users can view their own profile in a dedicated profile page.
- FR-PROFILE-002: Users can view other users’ profiles from appropriate entry points (e.g., clicking avatar/name).
- FR-PROFILE-003: Profiles surface at least: avatar, display name, handle, bio, and basic engagement numbers if available.
- FR-PROFILE-004: If a user has incomplete profile information, the page should handle this gracefully (empty states, placeholders).

### 3.3 Profile Editing
- FR-EDIT-001: Users can edit display name, avatar, and bio.
- FR-EDIT-002: Changes should be reflected in subsequent profile views and navigation (e.g., header avatar).
- FR-EDIT-003: Validation rules for text fields (length limits, disallowed characters/words) are applied consistently.
- FR-EDIT-004: Editing flows include clear success/failure messaging.

### 3.4 Settings Page (Non-payment)
- FR-SETTINGS-001: Provide an account settings page reachable from navigation.
- FR-SETTINGS-002: Settings include at minimum:
  - Email visibility or similar basic privacy toggle (exact options to be refined later).
  - Basic notification preferences at a coarse level (on/off or a small number of categories, not a full matrix).
  - Account-level actions placeholders (e.g., “Delete account” link pointing to existing or future flow).
- FR-SETTINGS-003: Settings changes persist and apply consistently across sessions.

### 3.5 Avatar Upload
- FR-AVATAR-001: Users can upload a profile image.
- FR-AVATAR-002: Basic validations: supported file types and size limits.
- FR-AVATAR-003: Users can replace an existing avatar.
- FR-AVATAR-004: Users can remove an avatar and fallback to a default representation.
- FR-AVATAR-005: Avatar updates propagate to key UI surfaces (profile page, navigation header, etc.).

### 3.6 Layout & Navigation
- FR-LAYOUT-001: Introduce a reusable app shell/layout structure that other pages can plug into (header/navigation + content).
- FR-LAYOUT-002: Navigation should include entry points for:
  - Home/Feed.
  - Profile.
  - Settings.
- FR-LAYOUT-003: Navigation state clearly indicates the current active section.
- FR-LAYOUT-004: Layout and navigation work on desktop and mobile-width viewports (exact breakpoints/UX left to UI/UX task).

